\par <I> <h> }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\fs24\lang2057 THE WAY I SEE IT}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par  <h> }{<#/> }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Our nation suffers when we propagate tribalism}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par  }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The way I see it is that, any Kenyan who thinks that tribalistic jingoism can redress past real or imaginary ills, is merely wishing destruction upon himself, his people and the nation.
\par <#/>That is so because tribalism in all its manifestations eats into the very fabric of society, saps its self-sustaining juices and leaves gangrenous rot - the last of the steps in the collapse of the management of the nation-state.
\par <#/>Let tribalism not be confused with ethnicity or the peculiarities of a person's coming f
rom a certain region in Kenya, speaking a specific language, eating specific foods, dressing in a manner peculiar to the tribe, observing taboos prescribed by the tribe and doing whatever else that pertains to the mores of his ethnic group.
\par <h> }{<#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057  Cultural traits}{\fs24\lang2057  </h> 
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 
One did not choose where to be born. <#/>I was born on the slopes of Mount Kenya, you were born on the shores of Lake Victoria, another Kenyan was born on the shores of the Indian Ocean, yet another in the heat of the Turkana desert. <#
/>By virtue of being born in different places without choice, we grow up adopting the cultural traits of the particular ethnic group in which we were born.
\par <#/>There is no crime or moral perversion in identifying with one's cultural background. <#/>That is why I agree with Chinua Achebe in his book }{\i\fs24\lang2057 The Trouble with Nigeria}{\fs24\lang2057 
 that, "Everyone agrees that there are manifestations of tribal culture which we cannot condemn; for example, peculiar habits of dress, food, language, music, etc. <#/>In fact many of thes
e manifestations are positive and desirable and confer richness on our national culture.\rdblquote 
\par <#/>What then is this beast called tribalism? <#/>I will go by the definition given by the Parliamentary Select Committee on Unemployment some years ago as quoted by Professor Mbithi in his book }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Rural Sociology and Rural Development}{
\fs24\lang2057 : " ... a person given to tribalism sees all issues in terms of tribalism.
\par <quote_><X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>"Thus, for example, if he is an arbiter in an issue, he sees members of his tribe as oppressed and 
members of the other tribe as oppressors ... this misinterpretation of the facts always in favour of one's own tribesmen is the worst thing that can happen to a nation because it engenders counteraction from others, an atmosphere of intensifying distrust 
and in the end a vicious circle in which it becomes impossible to extricate the truth. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 One ceases to distinguish truth as borne out by facts and falsity created by his own imagination}{\fs24\lang2057 .}{\v\fs24\lang2057 "}{
\fs24\lang2057 <quote/></X>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Examine that statement against what a certain leader said recently. <#/>He was talking from the point of view of an arbiter who cannot dispense fairness since he starts from the premise of the tribe above anything else.
\par <#/>The scary scenario which could erupt from that kind of statement is what the Parlia
mentary Select Committee described as "counteraction," that is, the ethnic group being accused of robbery reacting in its own manner to the threats of being "silenced" and being made to "lie low like an envelope".
\par <#/>The group that is being threatened (God forbid that it ever happens) could decide to say: "Why do they think that it is only us that can bleed? <#/>They should also know that they have blood and we could make them bleed." <X_>}{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 That is the trauma that every peace loving Kenyan would shudder to think of.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\v 
<#/>Tribalism may not necessarily breed violence, but there is one thing that it certainly brings forth. <#/>It is what Chinua Achebe calls "social injustice and the cult of mediocrity". <#/>I agree with the Nigerian writer when he says that "
the cult of mediocrity will bring the wheels of modernisation grinding to a halt throughout the land".
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031\cgrid {\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 I will quote from }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 The Trouble with Nigeria}{\v\fs24\lang2057  to illustrate how the cult of mediocrity is nurtured: }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 "Let us take a hypothetical case where two candidates - `A' and `B' - apply to fill a very important and strategic position. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
`A' has the right qualifications of competence and character, but is of the "wrong" tribe while `B', less qualified belongs to the "right" tribe, and so gets the job. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 "A" goes away embittered. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
`B' throws a party then messes up the job.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 "The greatest sufferer is the nation itself which has to contain the legitimate grievance of a wronged citizen; accommodate the incompetence of the favoured citizen and, more importan
t and of greater scope, endure a general decline of morale and subversion of efficiency caused by an erratic system of performance and reward.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 He later adds that, "whereas tribalism might win enough votes to install a reactionary jingoist in a tribal ghetto," it will arrest the process of positive change.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 That will happen because a mediocre appointed into a position of power just because he belongs to the "right" tribe does not have the intelligence to carry out his work. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The worst that will hap
pen to him after he fails to execute the nation-building task before him is be replaced by yet another tribesman and perpetuate the cult of mediocrity because the replacement might be equally mentally bankrupt.
\par <h> }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 Process of ruin}{\v\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 That means that there will be continuity in the process of ruining the country and discontinuity in the business of oiling the wheels of development.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The corollary to that is that tribalism can only be practised by those in privileged positions. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The privilege
d have the power and wealth to discriminate against other people because of their place of birth. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Your peasant mother may derogatorily refer to my peasant mother in terms that sound tribalistic, but that does not make her a tribalist. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 To quote Prof
essor Mbithi, " ... your mother might refer to my mother as `people from beyond the ridge', `the my-language non-speakers,' `the queer mannerism people,' and even `those who don't get circumcised', but that does not make her a tribalist."
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 She can only be a tribalist if she has favours to dish out, and in doing so gives a disproportionately large chunk of the national cake to her tribesmen and women. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
That is because in a modern nation-state, there would be no tribalism if there was no national cake to share out.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 It is in the process of sharing out the national cake that feelings of family, clan and tribe come into play. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
It is when jobs and import licence are allocated, promotions affected, plots being shared out and bank loans given without collateral that the retrogressive practice of tribalism comes into play. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
That is when we hear such things as, "So-and-so has looked at people from home well; he gave Bob and Julie plots where he works as DC."
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 There can only be individual tribalists within a tribal group. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 An ethnic group is not a <-/homogenuous> whole; it is made up of people with different inclinations. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
It has privileged and non-privileged people. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 It has opportunists and patriots; sycophants and true nationalists; grabbers and honest citizens. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
That is, people with different attitudes towards national values.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 That, of course, does not mean that leaders in specific tribal (call them ethnic groups if you want to use a euphemism) communities cannot and do not try to ral
ly members of their tribe into discriminating against other communities. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The leaders will use their privileged positions to charm the rest of the community into believing that they are under threat from another community. }{\v 
<#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 That particular community will live under the illusion that the real enemies are another community.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The worst that can happen is for a community, to cite Professor Mbithi, to feel that it is not "receiving as many loans, roads schools, visits from officials, extension officers,
 etc" because then "they are likely to articulate this relative deprivation by increasing their "visibility" or "consciousness" by being reactionary and perceiving large systems (nation-states) and the dominant sub-systems as oppressors or "those who bene
fit while we suffer".
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The dangers that could pockmark this country if tribalism was let to go on unchecked are just too painfully clear and we have the chance to act before the worst happens.}{\fs24\lang2057  </X>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
