\par <I> <h> }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\fs24\lang2057 BOUQUETS & BARBS}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par <h> }{<#/> }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Honesty: one little word that makes a difference}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Mwai Kibaki, that urbane, extremely competent technocrat and agile politician has become famous fo
r his unique contribution to Kenya's development and rare ability to come out on top of tribulations which would deflate lesser men. <#/>He is quite fearless too.
\par <#/>This week, he comes in for a bouquet for exposing , yet again, another admirable facet of his character, and one which is increasingly difficult to find in many local politicians - honesty.
\par <#/>Lately, there have been several press reports, extensively detailing the rot in which many of the local health institutions are mired in. <#/>The decre
pit New Nyanza General Hospital (also referred to as Russia Hospital) in Kisumu, was singled out for particular censure, in this instance by a write-up in the }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Kenya Times}{\fs24\lang2057 .
\par <#/>In keeping with the tradition that all of you readers should be familiar with by
 now, a politician, Mr Miruka Owuor, who represents the Nyando constituency, came out strongly against the newspaper which he accused of "alarmist reporting" about the hospital. <#/>But in this, as in almost every other instance that the media has been cr
iticised of misreporting, the Press was right.
\par <#/>And we have Mr Kibaki to thank for this. <#/>Following the report, he toured health facilities in Nyanza Province - including the hospital in question - and verified that the media reports were factual. <#/>He said as much.
\par <#/>It was true that the hospital was a shambles, it was true that it was teetering on the brink of collapse, true that its mortuary was in a pathetic state. <#/>Almost every department and facility within the institution was wanting in s
ome way. <#/>That is what had been said in the media and Mr Kibaki verified it.
\par <#/>His action is commendable for its own sake. <#/>It is also commendable because it brings into extremely sharp focus the more common, dishonest, bumbling attempts at decepti
on and cover-up which we have learnt to expect from most of our politicians. <#/>Had Mr Kibaki not gone to Kisumu, Mr Owuor's misleading statement would most probably have won the day.
\par <#/>Regrettably for the health of local politics and the development of
 this country, half-truths and flagrant distortions of truth have virtually been institutionalised. <#/>Politicians will deny the existence of a disease epidemic, the shortage of an essential commodity, the incompetence of a public institution, etc, when 
such an issue is beyond debate.
\par <#/>By doing this, they have abetted crime, sabotaged efforts to improve the delivery of services through criticism, and misled multitudes of credulous <ea/>wananchi who take most of what the leaders say as gospel truth. <#/>
It has become so prevalent that it has, counter-productively, bred a dangerous cynicism in those who can see through the lies. <#/>It is a cynicism which makes them disbelieve the politicians even on the rare times that they may be telling the truth.

\par <#/>I
t is futile to remind them at this point that honesty and justice are inseparable, that they cheat themselves more by misleading the public, and that at this point in time, many people may listen to what they say but only a handful believe. <#/>Mr Kibaki 
is clearly aware of this and he gets a bouquet for not trying to insist that black is white, just because he wants it to be white.
\par <#/>Different view over the sack
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 Another bouquet goes to the handful of people who, publicly or privately, have raised thi
s question: To what extent have workers in the private or public sector been kicked out of their jobs for reasons other than incompetence or gross insubordination? <#/>In other words, how often has the threat, or the act of sacking been precipitated by re
asons other than the purely professional?
\par <#/>I do not <-/>not know, but I think it is a significant question particularly at this time when the debate on the efficiency and effectiveness of parastatal and other public institutions is raging.
\par <#/>Often, if 
not all the time, the public has assumed that when an individual is sacked, particularly from a responsible position, it is because he did not perform competently. <#/>He either made an indefensible management decision, stole money or did something else e
qually unacceptable}{\v\fs24\lang2057 . }{\fs24\lang2057 <X}{\v\fs24\lang2057 _>}{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 But wait a minute. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
It can be argued, fairly convincingly, that extraneous issues - politics, jealousy, personal differences, rivalry and pique - do play a significant part in such matters.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Numerous scenarios can be drawn up. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
An officer refuses to approve a deal in which another powerful party is interested in; a senior manager makes a right decision but one which is not in the interest of another "tough guy"; an officer refuses to grant a favour (usually illegally sou
ght) to one who is influential, etc.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The possibility has been raised that in extreme cases, being too efficient can be held against one, particularly if such efficiency might lead to the unearthing of records which detail dubious transactions. }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 All these and more, I am told, are possible.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Because of the serious possibilities they raise, and because decisions to sack will continue to be made, I leave it to you reader to mull over the matter. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
I hope it will engross you sufficiently to agree with me that those who raise such questions deserve a bouquet.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Habit insults those in need }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The barb this week is directed at employers who, deliberately or otherwise, are fond of putting job-seekers through a lot of mental anguish and apprehension by 
not acknowledging job applications which they (employers) have invited in the first place.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 It is now commonplace to find employers who place advertisements inviting applications from unemployed people and then ignoring those applications. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 They neit
her acknowledge receipt of the applications nor inform the applicants that their applications were unsuccessful.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Needless to say, this is wrong. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 It is unethical and callous. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The least one can expect from a serious employer is a note that the ap
plication has been received and that it is either being considered or that it does not meet the basic requirements and hence, it is unsuccessful. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
If employers do not intend to reply to every Tom Dick and Harry who answers to an advertisement, they should indicate clearly that only those applicants who meet certain requirements will be notified.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Sharing the barb with these employers who ignore applications are those who invite applications for jobs which they have already filled. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 In such instance
s, the advertisements are placed for the record. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Again, this is a despicably immoral practice, one which has no place in civilised society. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 You will be excused if 
you ask whether, going by some of the practices rampant in this country, we can lay claim to being civilised.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 However, the bottom line is whether such practices as cited here can be condoned because worse are <_/practiced> elsewhere in the system. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
The answer is no, and hence this barb to those employers who have no respect for protocol.
\par <h> }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 A thief by any other name ...}{\v\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 It is expected that once someone has enjoyed services or taken goods on credit, he should pay for them. this is the law and, you all must agree, it is a good law. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
But there are those among us who like free things, and can even cheat or steal in order not to pay. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 These people earn a huge barb today.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 You must be familiar with them. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The people who go into restaurants and eat, drink and then shove the bills into ashtrays and walk out through the back door leaving the problem with the hapless wai
ters; tenants who vacate houses without clearing their water and electricity accounts; hotel residents who sneak out surreptitiously leaving their personal effects because the bill they have run up is much higher than the total cost of their belongings, e
tc.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 They come in all shades but share one common character - a thieving streak. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 There is no other word for it. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
To enjoy services and not pay for it is to steal. It is quite shameful that some of the people who do these are otherwise respectable men and women of means. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 They merely do not want to pay. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
They are a breed of undesirables who deserve much worse than this barb I hurl their way. }{\fs24\lang2057 </X>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
