\par <h> }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\fs24\lang2057 This censorship smacks of sanitising rot in society}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The way I see it is that banning plays from being staged in Kenya is a very uncreative role on the part of censors.
\par <#/>Unfortunately, this is the tragic drama now unfolding; an unfortunate script done by censors who hide behind all manner of excuses to frustrate the development of drama in Kenya.
\par <#/>In about a month, the censors' axe has felled two scripts that are well known, one of which has won international appeal in its novel form.
\par <#/>First to be axed was}{\i\fs24\lang2057  Ngahika Ndenda}{\fs24\lang2057  jointly scripted by two self-exiled Kenyans: Professor Ngugi was Thiong'o and Ngugi wa Mirii. <#/>The Gikuyu play was intended for staging by Sar
akasi Players at their Kenyatta International Conference Centre basement hall last month.
\par <#/>Then last week the curtain fell prematurely for Theatre Yetu's adaptation of George Orwell's novel, }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Animal Farm}{\fs24\lang2057 , which they were to stage as a Kiswahili play, }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Shamba la Wanyama}{\fs24\lang2057 
. <#/>They had support <-/form> the British Council in Nairobi and were to stage it at the Kenya National Theatre.
\par <h> }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Eleventh Hour}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 It was reported that the censors arrived at the eleventh hour before production and produced a 
banning order saying, "it is deemed appropriate that the licence (for public production) not be given now, but Government officials are still studying the script".
\par <#/>In the case of}{\i\fs24\lang2057  Ngahika Ndenda}{\fs24\lang2057 , there was no such protocol. <#/>It was a case of "bring b
ack the licence we gave you and get out of here before we show you what we are capable of doing to you". <#/>Those who came to demand the licence back were kind of saying that the actors and actresses had already committed a crime by imagining that they c
ould stage the play.
\par <#/>}{\i\fs24\lang2057 Ngahika Ndenda }{\fs24\lang2057 and}{\i\fs24\lang2057  Animal Farm}{\fs24\lang2057 
 are not some of those documents that have been declared seditious. <#/>They are freely available in the bookshops and the former is published locally. <#/>In other words, they are not circulated in the
 dark in forfeited bunkers. <#/>You can buy them as freely as you can buy and read the Kanu manifesto and a copy of the Bible.
\par <#/>That notwithstanding, }{\i\fs24\lang2057 Ngahika Ndenda }{\fs24\lang2057 has been banned from public performance before when it was staged at Kamirithu, Limuru, 
by villagers. <#/>The open-air theatre where it was performed to record audiences was subsequently razed down }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>idiom}{\fs24\lang2057  by administration officials who declared it an "anti-development" forum.
\par <#/>One could guess why it attracts the <-_censors><+_censor's>
 pen so easily. <#/>One reason is that the name of Ngugi wa Thiong'o, Kenya's foremost novelist, makes some people get goose pimples immediately. <#/>They get jitters, agitated and even paranoid when his name is mentioned although I doubt whether they hav
e all read his books.
\par <#/>The man has earned himself all the negative superlatives that the Kenyan political dictionary has. <#/>he has been called a "servant of foreign masters", a "peddler of foreign ideologies", "enemy of development", "unpatriotic" and 
earned himself other vitriol from the blazing mouths of politicians.
\par <#/>No censor would, of course, like to be held responsible for licensing a play written by a man who has been declared a hydra-headed monster. <#/>Surprisingly, however, Sarakisi Players
 had been granted a stage licence and were already rehearsing before it was withdrawn. <X_>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 <#/>The censor must have paused and said: }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 "Hey, wait a minute. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Isn't this play by the same Ngugi wa <-/Thing'o>, the Salman Rushdie of Kenya? }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 I had forgotten that he was an enemy of the people. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Now that I have remembered that, I declare that the play is not considered right for public consumption on stage. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Get back }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>idiom}{\v\fs24\lang2057  that licence."
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The other possible reason for the ban is that }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Ngahika Ndenda}{\v\fs24\lang2057  and }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Animal Farm}{\v\fs24\lang2057  tell uncomfortable truths about society. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
They satirise social ills bred by ill leadership leading to inequitable distribution of resources. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 They unravel the process in which the underdog discovers himself and prepares to throw
 off the yoke of repression that has weighed him down for a long time.
\par <h> }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 Stage licences}{\v\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 It would be tragic if the plays were denied stage licences for the second reason for it would be a transgression of one of art's prime <-_role><+_roles> in a developing country: }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
To be a barometer of society by praising and criticising.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Whereas some uniformed people say that drama is uniformed people say that drama is <ea/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 mchezo}{\v\fs24\lang2057 , meaning that it is some sort of cowing on stage, it is not so. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
It is the serious business of re-enacting life on stage to bring out its inadequacies and fullness. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 While playing that role, theatre naturally treads on sore toes. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
It pokes a finger into the sores of some people. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 It has the right to do so painful as it is to the subjects handled. 
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Drama dwells on conflicts and the best theatre is that which intensifies realistic human conflicts on stage. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Such is the case with }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Shamba la Wanyama}{\v\fs24\lang2057  and }{
\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Ngahika Ndenda.}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 They may be unpalatable to some people because they tell things that are better hidden in the closet, but drama has that role of stripping naked even kings.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The ban on the stage productions of the two plays is also unfortunate because they were to be staged in languages that do not get to be used often enough on stage. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Plays in Kenyan languages other than in Kiswahili have had a very small stake on Kenyan stages while those in Kiswahili have also not made an impact.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 It is such attempts as staging }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Ngahika Ndenda }{\v\fs24\lang2057 and }{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Shamba la Wanyama }{\v\fs24\lang2057 that give hope for the future of a truly Kenyan theatre in Kenyan languages. }{
\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Such plays should, therefore, be encouraged and not discouraged.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 There are those who will shoot up and say: "Plays in Kenyan languages will promote tribalism! }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Let us have plays in English for the sake of national unity."
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 That is an escapist and retrogressive argument because tribalism is not prompted by the language one speaks but by the cats ones does. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 You may speak all the English there is in
 the world, but be the leading tribalist by your deeds which will include giving all the best jobs to your tribesmen.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 I have heard it said in the past that most Kenyan plays are political and, therefore, not classifiable as drama. there have even been 
proposals that more emphasis be put on such playwrights as William Shakespeare allegedly because their works are not political. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Such recommendations are made out of ignorance because Shakespeare is political depending on how you look at his plays. }{\v <#/>}{\i\v\fs24\lang2057 Othelo}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
, for example, which seems to be a tale of lovers, has a political message if you look at it creatively. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Politics is part of drama and that it is how it should be.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The way I see it then is that,}{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>punct}{\v\fs24\lang2057  censors should realise that dram is not expected to pamper ill institutions. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
It has the right to provoke so that we know where we started to limp. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Sad will be the day when theatre will be turned }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 <&/>grammar}{\v\fs24\lang2057  into a deodorant to sanitise rot in a society}{
\fs24\lang2057 . </X>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
