\par <h> }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Darkness at night puts airport bosses in a spot}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 The management of the "ultra-modern" Jomo Kenyatta Internation
al Airport (JKIA) comes in for a major barb this week for letting one of the more pre-eminent symbols of successful public investment fall on hard times when it should be right at the cutting edge of the latest developments in airport management.
\par <#/>There
 are a number of things which certainly could do with a bit of freshening up at that place, not least the rest rooms and refreshment facilities. <#/>But the incident which specifically attracts this barb happened this week and is, according to information
 gathered there, not unusual.
\par <#/>On Tuesday night, the airport was plunged into darkness for lengthy intervals forcing delays at check-in counters and cash <-_bureaus><+_bureaux>, discontinuation of service at the bars and general confusion as travellers a
rriving to check in found themselves in darkness. <#/>At one point, one of the airlines had to use car headlights to provide light for passengers checking in at its counter.
\par <#/>The general blackout, although quite unusual and unexpected for a busy airport
, is not the worst of lapses either. <#/>The unforgivable one was the almost total cut off of the power supply which lights the runways and the markers which lead in aircraft wishing to land.
\par <#/>The effect of this was that a number of planes could not lan
d, flight connections were thrown into disarray and airlines and travellers were forced to spend extra money for a lapse they had nothing to do with. <#/>I know of one KLM flight which was scheduled to connect through Nairobi for Johannesburg to Amsterdam
 but which, after circling the Nairobi skies for almost four hours, had to go and land in Mombasa. <#/>The consequences of this are all too clear.
\par <#/>Now, I am not an airport administrator. <#/>But knowing what airports are and the possible accidents or ac
ts of sabotage which can be happen there, I seem to think that provision of sufficient light at all times is an absolute imperative. <#/>Does JKIA not have back-up generators which should switch on immediately power fails? <#/>I think it does, but I wonde
r how serviceable they are?
\par <#/>It is my submission that operations of an airport can be grounded for any number of factors, but not because of an ordinary hitch like a power failure.
\par <#/>Certainly, travellers into or out of the country are not going to be 
amused when they learn that their travel arrangements have been messed up because the airport which claims to be tops in Africa could not receive or send out planes. <#/>It is a shameful lapse which glib excuses cannot justify and for which the administra
tor there gets a barb.
\par <h> }{<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\fs24\lang2057 Onward march against hunger}{\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {<#/>The bouquet goes to Kenya's farmers, big or small, wherever they may be for the hard work and sacrifices they have to overcome to feed this nation. <#/>A 
quick dash last week through Central and Rift Valley provinces to the western part of the country convinced me that <-_farmers><+_farmers'> sensibilities, opinions and ideas on the management of this country may be overlooked, but we cannot ignore the nob
ility of their work.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031\cgrid {<#/>}{\fs24\lang2057 
Farming, for those who do not know, is one of the most unpredictable economic undertakings. <#/>There is the permanent fear that the weather will let one down just when the crop has reached the stage where either too much rain or su
n - or lack of either - will destroy it. <#/>Often, the rain does not come at all. <#/>Unlike in other activities, farmers in general are not insured against losses which may be a result from such natural hazards.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {<X_>}{\v <#/>Often also, and particularly for (
small scale) maize farmers, the returns on the investment - basically the high production costs - <-_is><+_are> not sufficient recompense for the capital and energy inputs which go into production.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031\cgrid {\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 But that has not stopped the farmers from shrugging off disappointments and proceeding with the task at hand. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
They get into debt to plough, get into more debt to cultivate and yet more debt to harvest and prepare the harvest for the market. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Returns, when they come, merely cover the debts and leave little for anything else.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The cycle is repeated yearly. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 No wonder poverty is so closely associated with rural life.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\v <#/>It appears to me that these farmers have a more legitimate case to expect that their loans should be written off, rather than those
 of huge monopoly-holding parastatals whose inability to post profits is the result of poor organisational structures, political interference and management failures.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031\cgrid {\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 As they wait for salvation from those able to give it, they continue to work to feed Kenyans. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
It is an admirable task for which farmers richly deserve a bouquet.
\par <h> }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 A high price for obstinacy}{\v\fs24\lang2057  </h> 
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Fallen Malian strongman Moussa Traore also comes in for a barb this week for plunging his country into a state of violence and un
certainty, merely because he refused to <-_the> accept the writing on the wall and leave office gracefully.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Now, in a perfect reversal of roles, the persecutor has become the prisoner of the formerly persecuted. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Poetic justice at its best, if you ask me.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 You will remember that Moussa Traore seized power forcibly in 1968, became president in 1969 and "legitimised" his government in 1979 in a sham election involving only his party, the Democratic Union of Malian People. }{\v <#/>
}{\v\fs24\lang2057 His reign has been a revelation of centralisation of power, creation of a personality cult, brutal suppression of any form of dissent, economic mismanagement and abuse of human rights.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 You will recall also that in the past two years when multi-party politics and democracy have been on everyone's lips, Mr Traore was one of the very few African leaders to stick to the one-party doctrine. }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 Well, it couldn't last forever. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Not with the people aroused and actively demanding change.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Moussa Traore's bubble burst earlier this year when what had been low-key rumbles erupted into 100,000-strong civilian demonstrations. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 The military reacted predictably. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
A couple hundred were killed but the momentum for democracy did not falter. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Other soldiers came in to save the day and only restored some calm on the promise that far-reaching political changes were in the offing. }{\v <#/>}{
\v\fs24\lang2057 Well, they better be serious.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \lang2057\cgrid {\v <#/>In Traore's fall is a poignant message for leaders who refuse to recognise and accept change. <#/>They cannot win. <#/
>And another thing to note. <#/>When the people rise to demand what they know is denied them, nothing can stop them. <#/>Traore refused to acknowledge this fact of history and he gets a major barb to garnish the indignity he must be feeling about being hu
stled out of the kingly opulence of his official residence to the indescribable bareness of a dark prison cell.
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031\cgrid {\v\fs24\lang2057 <h> }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057  }{\b\v\fs24\lang2057 Only dunces stay right there}{\v\fs24\lang2057  </h>
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 There are drivers who are remarkable only for their ignorance of traffic regulations or their disdain for the expected conduct on the roads. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
Today, I hurl a barb at those who, on a dual-carriage way, drive permanently on the right-hand side lane, a lane which is provided for over-taking.
\par }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 You will see them. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 Laden battered pick-ups huffing an
d puffing as they take on <-_a> <+_an> incline, tractors and lorries straining to overtake when they cannot and thereby blocking the over-taking lane. }{\v <#/>}{\v\fs24\lang2057 
